{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4577].
  {panel}

I would like to have some control over new issues when they are entered - i.e. specify permissions required, specify validation and post-create actions. To be more concrete I would like to fill some internal fields and assign issue in my custom plugin.

The nice point to implement this function is "initial" transition i.e. transition to "New" state.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4569].
  {panel}

Some customers need to be able to view the unique issue id, rather than the issue key - we should display this on the view issue page

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4545].
  {panel}

For certain industries there is a need to provide robust logging of who performed an activity and the current JIRA model of a single login per session does not suffice.  Is there any plans to development the security further such that credentials can be requested at some points in the workflow?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4529].
  {panel}

currently, release notes and other reports URL use version id.

when using maven or other build engines, we'd like to generate a report including the jira report URL, with version name, since only jira knows about version id.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4521].
  {panel}

We found out by surprise that the assignee of an issue created by CreateIssueHandler is the first valid user in the recipient list. I would like to be able to set a parameter (assignee=xxx) that defines who all issues are assigned to, everytime, regardless of who is on the recipient list. This parameter should take either a valid user name, or "defaultassignee" for the default assignee for the project. For now, I have to educate everyone to be careful with who they put first in the recipient list.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4517].
  {panel}

Any possiblity of getting multipart notification emails? As i use both HTML and Text email viewers.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4515].
  {panel}

Currently in the project Default Assignee options there is "Project Lead" and (if enabled) "Unassigned".  There should be a third option, "Disabled (force selection)", which if chosen, would force the user to choose from the available list of users.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4504].
  {panel}

We would like to have issue types assigned to a project category, so that only specific projects or projects within a specific Project Category have access to an issue type.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-4503].
  {panel}

We use a project category to group projects and would like the ability to have a custom field scoped to a project category. This would give us some form of project 'inheritence' that we require when creating many projects
